people%20with%20clarity%20and%20realism%2C%20was%20often%20likened%20to%20Anton%20Chekhov%2C%20the%2019th%20century%20Russian%20known%20for%20his%20brilliant%20short%20stories%20-%20a%20comparison%20the%20Swedish%20Academy%20cited%20in%20honoring%20her%20with%20the%20Nobel%20Prize.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ECalling%20her%20a%20%26quot%3Bmaster%20of%20the%20contemporary%20short%20story%2C%26quot%3B%20the%20Academy%20also%20said%3A%20%26quot%3BHer%20texts%20often%20feature%20depictions%20of%20everyday%20but%20decisive%20events%2C%20epiphanies%20of%20a%20kind%2C%20that%20illuminate%20the%20surrounding%20story%20and%20let%20existential%20questions%20appear%20in%20a%20flash%20of%20lightning.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20an%20interview%20with%20the%20Canadian%20Broadcasting%20Corporation%20after%20winning%20the%20Nobel%2C%20Munro%20said%2C%20%26quot%3BI%20think%20my%20stories%20have%20gotten%20around%20quite%20remarkably%20for%20short%20stories%2C%20and%20I%20would%20really%20hope%20that%20this%20would%20make%20people%20see%20the%20short%20story%20as%20an%20important%20art%2C%20not%20just%20something%20that%20you%20played%20around%20with%20until%20you'd%20got%20a%20novel%20written.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EHer%20works%20included%3A%20%26quot%3BDance%20of%20the%20Happy%20Shades%26quot%3B%20(1968)%2C%20%26quot%3BLives%20of%20Girls%20and%20Women%26quot%3B%20(1971)%2C%20%26quot%3BWho%20Do%20You%20Think%20You%20Are%3F%26quot%3B%20(1978)%2C%20%26quot%3BThe%20Moons%20of%20Jupiter%26quot%3B%20(1982)%2C%20%26quot%3BHateship%2C%20Friendship%2C%20Courtship%2C%20Loveship%2C%20Marriage%26quot%3B%20(2001)%2C%20%26quot%3BRunaway%26quot%3B%20(2004)%2C%20%26quot%3BThe%20View%20from%20Castle%20Rock%26quot%3B%20(2006)%2C%20%26quot%3BToo%20Much%20Happiness%26quot%3B%20(2009)%20and%20%26quot%3BDear%20Life%26quot%3B%20(2012).%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20characters%20in%20her%20stories%20were%20often%20girls%20and%20women%20who%20lead%20seemingly%20unexceptional%20lives%20but%20struggle%20with%20tribulations%20ranging%20from%20sexual%20abuse%20and%20stifling%20marriages%20to%20repressed%20love%20and%20the%20ravages%20of%20aging.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EHer%20story%20of%20a%20woman%20who%20starts%20losing%20her%20memory%20and%20agrees%20to%20enter%20a%20nursing%20home%20titled%20%26quot%3BThe%20Bear%20Came%20Over%20the%20Mountain%2C%26quot%3B%20from%20%26quot%3BHateship%2C%20Friendship%2C%20Courtship%2C%20Loveship%2C%20Marriage%2C%26quot%3B%20was%20adapted%20into%20the%20Oscar-nominated%202006%20film%20%26quot%3BAway%20From%20Her%2C%26quot%3B%20directed%20by%20fellow%20Canadian%20Sarah%20Polley.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E'SHAME%20AND%20EMBARRASSMENT'%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ECanadian%20novelist%20Margaret%20Atwood%2C%20writing%20in%20the%20Guardian%20after%20Munro%20won%20the%20Nobel%2C%20summarized%20her%20work%20by%20saying%3A%20%26quot%3BShame%20and%20embarrassment%20are%20driving%20forces%20for%20Munro's%20characters%2C%20just%20as%20perfectionism%20in%20the%20writing%20has%20been%20a%20driving%20force%20for%20her%3A%20getting%20it%20down%2C%20getting%20it%20right%2C%20but%20also%20the%20impossibility%20of%20that.%20Munro%20chronicles%20failure%20much%20more%20often%20than%20she%20chronicles%20success%2C%20because%20the%20task%20of%20the%20writer%20has%20failure%20built%20in.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAmerican%20novelist%20Jonathan%20Franzen%20wrote%20in%202005%2C%20%26quot%3BReading%20Munro%20puts%20me%20in%20that%20state%20of%20quiet%20reflection%20in%20which%20I%20think%20about%20my%20own%20life%3A%20about%20the%20decisions%20I've%20made%2C%20the%20things%20I've%20done%20and%20haven't%20done%2C%20the%20kind%20of%20person%20I%20am%2C%20the%20prospect%20of%20death.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20short%20story%2C%20a%20style%20more%20popular%20in%20the%2019th%20and%20early%2020th%20century%2C%20has%20long%20taken%20a%20back%20seat%20to%20the%20novel%20in%20popular%20tastes%20-%20and%20in%20attracting%20awards.%20But%20Munro%20was%20able%20to%20infuse%20her%20short%20stories%20with%20a%20richness%20of%20plot%20and%20depth%20of%20detail%20usually%20more%20characteristic%20of%20full-length%20novels.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BFor%20years%20and%20years%2C%20I%20thought%20that%20stories%20were%20just%20practice%2C%20'til%20I%20got%20time%20to%20write%20a%20novel.%20Then%20I%20found%20that%20they%20were%20all%20I%20could%20do%20and%20so%20I%20faced%20that.%20I%20suppose%20that%20my%20trying%20to%20get%20so%20much%20into%20stories%20has%20been%20a%20compensation%2C%26quot%3B%20Munro%20told%20the%20New%20Yorker%20magazine%20in%202012.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EShe%20was%20the%20second%20Canadian-born%20writer%20to%20win%20the%20Nobel%20literature%20prize%20but%20the%20first%20with%20a%20distinctly%20Canadian%20identity.%20Saul%20Bellow%2C%20who%20won%20in%201976%2C%20was%20born%20in%20Quebec%20but%20raised%20in%20Chicago%20and%20was%20widely%20seen%20as%20an%20American%20writer.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EMunro%20also%20won%20the%20Man%20Booker%20International%20Prize%20in%202009%20and%20the%20Giller%20Prize%20-%20Canada's%20most%20high-profile%20literary%20award%20-%20twice.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAlice%20Laidlaw%20was%20born%20to%20a%20hard-pressed%20family%20of%20farmers%20on%20July%2010%2C%201931%2C%20in%20Wingham%2C%20a%20small%20town%20in%20the%20region%20of%20southwestern%20Ontario%20that%20serves%20as%20the%20setting%20for%20many%20of%20her%20stories%2C%20and%20started%20writing%20in%20her%20teens.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EMunro%20originally%20began%20writing%20short%20stories%20while%20a%20stay-at-home%20mother.%20She%20intended%20to%20someday%20write%20a%20novel%2C%20but%20said%20that%20with%20three%20children%20she%20was%20never%20able%20to%20find%20the%20time%20necessary.%20Munro%20began%20building%20a%20reputation%20when%20her%20stories%20started%20getting%20published%20in%20the%20New%20Yorker%20in%20the%201970s.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EShe%20married%20James%20Munro%20in%201951%20and%20moved%20to%20Victoria%2C%20British%20Columbia%2